efinitive authentication. Multiple independent outlets reported the note was Epstein's purported suicide note before the deadline, based on an official court unsealing. The \"purported\" language reflects responsible journalism rather than undermining the reporting's credibility—the proposition's standard is met when credible sources report these claims, even while noting authentication limitations. The court order itself characterizes the document as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein,\" and major outlets reported this characterization before the deadline. This appears to satisfy the \"credibly reported\" standard.\n\nYet the defendant raises a valid concern: reporting can credibly describe a claim without establishing its probable truth. The sources explicitly preserved uncertainty about authorship and intent rather than affirming them.\n\nWeighing both positions, I find the proposition demonstrated. The standard requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not authentication. Multiple independent outlets—Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP—along with the SDNY court order itself, all characterized the document as Epstein's suicide note before May 8. The \"purportedly\" language reflects responsible journalism while still reporting the attribution. The note's content and context support its characterization as a suicide-related communication. Public availability and credible reporting are established by preponderance.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782796144492,"responseId":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}}
