:{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":18099,"output":1112,"totalTokens":19211}},"type":"thinking_end"},"message":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"thinking":"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning","type":"thinking"},{"text":"I have reviewed the full arbitration record. The proposition asks whether, by May 8, 2026, a note was publicly available and **credibly reported** to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note or equivalent communication—not whether authorship was authenticated beyond doubt.\n\nThe admitted record establishes:\n1. **Public availability before deadline:** SDNY Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealed the note, directing the clerk to docket and release material described as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n2. **Credible reporting consensus:** Reuters (May 6), NPR (May 7), BBC (May 7), and AP (defense exhibit) all reported the public release and characterized the document as Epstein's purported suicide note or goodbye note, preserving the note's text including \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\"\n3. **Intent evidence:** The reported text, context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt), and consistent media/court framing support suicide-note or final-message interpretation.\n\nThe \"purported\" and \"not verified\" caveats reflect responsible journalism and the market rule's own wording—they do not negate that credible reporting established the required characterizations by preponderance.\n\n","type":"text"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that before May 8, 2026, a note was publicly released via SDNY court order (May 6) and credibly reported by Reuters, NPR, BBC, and AP as Epstein's purported suicide note with final-message language. The proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not conclusive authentication; the consistent characterization across independent outlets and the official court order satisfies this standard.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782796144492,"usage":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":18099,"output":1112,"totalTokens":19211}},"type":"message_update"}
{"aar_log_filter":{"content_index":1,"dropped_prefix_bytes":1270,"field":"text","message":"earlier repeated message_update events dropped","replaced_fields":2,"response_id":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","tail_bytes":0},"assistantMessageEvent":{"content":"I have reviewed the full arbitration record. The proposition asks whether, by May 8, 2026, a note was publicly available and **credibly reported** to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note or equivalent communication—not whether authorship was authenticated beyond doubt.\n\nThe admitted record establishes:\n1. **Public availability before deadline:** SDNY Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealed the note, directing the clerk to docket and release material described as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n2. **Credible reporting consensus:** Reuters (May 6), NPR (May 7), BBC (May 7), and AP (defense exhibit) all reported the public release and characterized the document as Epstein's purported suicide note or goodbye note, preserving the note's text including \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\"\n3. **Intent evidence:** The reported text, context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt), and consistent media/court framing support suicide-note or final-message interpretation.\n\nThe \"purported\" and \"not verified\" caveats reflect responsible journalism and the market rule's own wording—they do not negate that credible reporting established the required characterizations by preponderance.\n\n","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"thinking":"I've received the opportunity to vote. Let me analyze the case:\n\n**Proposition:** By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\n\n**Standard:** Preponderance of the evidence.\n\n**Key evidence admitted:**\n1. **PX-1 (SDNY Order):** Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealing a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" - proves official court release before deadline\n2. **PX-2 (Reuters):** May 6 report of federal judge releasing document described as suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, with note text\n3. **PX-3 (NPR):** May 7 report confirming public release, calls it \"goodbye note,\" preserves authentication caveats\n4. **PX-4 (BBC):** May 7 report corroborating public release and note characterization\n5. **DX-1 (AP):** Defense evidence confirming public release while emphasizing provenance caveats\n\n**Analysis:**\n- **Public availability:** Uncontested - the SDNY order unsealed the note on May 6, 2026, before the May 8 deadline\n- **Credibly reported:** Multiple major credible outlets (Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP) reported on the released note before May 8\n- **Written by Epstein:** All reports describe it as \"purportedly\" written by Epstein; none authenticate handwriting; DOJ hadn't authenticated it\n- **Intent as suicide note:** The note text (\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\") and context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt) support this characterization\n\nThe key question is whether \"credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note\" is satisfied by multiple credible outlets reporting it as a \"purported suicide note\" with explicit caveats about authentication.\n \nThe proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not definitive authentication. Multiple independent outlets reported the note was Epstein's purported suicide note before the deadline, based on an official court unsealing. The \"purported\" language reflects responsible journalism rather than undermining the reporting's credibility—the proposition's standard is met when credible sources report these claims, even while noting authentication limitations. The court order itself characterizes the document as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein,\" and major outlets reported this characterization before the deadline. This appears to satisfy the \"credibly reported\" standard.\n\nYet the defendant raises a valid concern: reporting can credibly describe a claim without establishing its probable truth. The sources explicitly preserved uncertainty about authorship and intent rather than affirming them.\n\nWeighing both positions, I find the proposition demonstrated. The standard requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not authentication. Multiple independent outlets—Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP—along with the SDNY court order itself, all characterized the document as Epstein's suicide note before May 8. The \"purportedly\" language reflects responsible journalism while still reporting the attribution. The note's content and context support its characterization as a suicide-related communication. Public availability and credible reporting are established by preponderance.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning","type":"thinking"},{"text":"","type":"text"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that before May 8, 2026, a note was publicly released via SDNY court order (May 6) and credibly reported by Reuters, NPR, BBC, and AP as Epstein's purported suicide note with final-message language. The proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not conclusive authentication; the consistent characterization across independent outlets and the official court order satisfies this standard.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782796144492,"usage":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":18099,"output":1112,"totalTokens":19211}},"type":"text_end"},"message":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"thinking":"I've received the opportunity to vote. Let me analyze the case:\n\n**Proposition:** By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\n\n**Standard:** Preponderance of the evidence.\n\n**Key evidence admitted:**\n1. **PX-1 (SDNY Order):** Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealing a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" - proves official court release before deadline\n2. **PX-2 (Reuters):** May 6 report of federal judge releasing document described as suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, with note text\n3. **PX-3 (NPR):** May 7 report confirming public release, calls it \"goodbye note,\" preserves authentication caveats\n4. **PX-4 (BBC):** May 7 report corroborating public release and note characterization\n5. **DX-1 (AP):** Defense evidence confirming public release while emphasizing provenance caveats\n\n**Analysis:**\n- **Public availability:** Uncontested - the SDNY order unsealed the note on May 6, 2026, before the May 8 deadline\n- **Credibly reported:** Multiple major credible outlets (Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP) reported on the released note before May 8\n- **Written by Epstein:** All reports describe it as \"purportedly\" written by Epstein; none authenticate handwriting; DOJ hadn't authenticated it\n- **Intent as suicide note:** The note text (\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\") and context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt) support this characterization\n\nThe key question is whether \"credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note\" is satisfied by multiple credible outlets reporting it as a \"purported suicide note\" with explicit caveats about authentication.\n \nThe proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not definitive authentication. Multiple independent outlets reported the note was Epstein's purported suicide note before the deadline, based on an official court unsealing. The \"purported\" language reflects responsible journalism rather than undermining the reporting's credibility—the proposition's standard is met when credible sources report these claims, even while noting authentication limitations. The court order itself characterizes the document as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein,\" and major outlets reported this characterization before the deadline. This appears to satisfy the \"credibly reported\" standard.\n\nYet the defendant raises a valid concern: reporting can credibly describe a claim without establishing its probable truth. The sources explicitly preserved uncertainty about authorship and intent rather than affirming them.\n\nWeighing both positions, I find the proposition demonstrated. The standard requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not authentication. Multiple independent outlets—Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP—along with the SDNY court order itself, all characterized the document as Epstein's suicide note before May 8. The \"purportedly\" language reflects responsible journalism while still reporting the attribution. The note's content and context support its characterization as a suicide-related communication. Public availability and credible reporting are established by preponderance.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning","type":"thinking"},{"text":"","type":"text"},{"arguments":{"args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that before May 8, 2026, a note was publicly released via SDNY court order (May 6) and credibly reported by Reuters, NPR, BBC, and AP as Epstein's purported suicide note with final-message language. The proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not conclusive authentication; the consistent characterization across independent outlets and the official court order satisfies this standard.\"}","tool":"aar_submit_council_vote"},"id":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","name":"mcp","type":"toolCall"}],"model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216","role":"assistant","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782796144492,"usage":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":18099,"output":1112,"totalTokens":19211}},"type":"message_update"}
{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":2,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that before May 8, 2026, a note was publicly released via SDNY court order (May 6) and credibly reported by Reuters, NPR, BBC, and AP as Epstein's purported suicide note with final-message language. The proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not conclusive authentication; the consistent characterization across independent outlets and the official court order satisfies this standard.\"}"}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I've received the opportunity to vote. Let me analyze the case:\n\n**Proposition:** By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\n\n**Standard:** Preponderance of the evidence.\n\n**Key evidence admitted:**\n1. **PX-1 (SDNY Order):** Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealing a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" - proves official court release before deadline\n2. **PX-2 (Reuters):** May 6 report of federal judge releasing document described as suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, with note text\n3. **PX-3 (NPR):** May 7 report confirming public release, calls it \"goodbye note,\" preserves authentication caveats\n4. **PX-4 (BBC):** May 7 report corroborating public release and note characterization\n5. **DX-1 (AP):** Defense evidence confirming public release while emphasizing provenance caveats\n\n**Analysis:**\n- **Public availability:** Uncontested - the SDNY order unsealed the note on May 6, 2026, before the May 8 deadline\n- **Credibly reported:** Multiple major credible outlets (Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP) reported on the released note before May 8\n- **Written by Epstein:** All reports describe it as \"purportedly\" written by Epstein; none authenticate handwriting; DOJ hadn't authenticated it\n- **Intent as suicide note:** The note text (\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\") and context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt) support this characterization\n\nThe key question is whether \"credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note\" is satisfied by multiple credible outlets reporting it as a \"purported suicide note\" with explicit caveats about authentication.\n \nThe proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not definitive authentication. Multiple independent outlets reported the note was Epstein's purported suicide note before the deadline, based on an official court unsealing. The \"purported\" language reflects responsible journalism rather than undermining the reporting's credibility—the proposition's standard is met when credible sources report these claims, even while noting authentication limitations. The court order itself characterizes the document as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein,\" and major outlets reported this characterization before the deadline. This appears to satisfy the \"credibly reported\" standard.\n\nYet the defendant raises a valid concern: reporting can credibly describe a claim without establishing its probable truth. The sources explicitly preserved uncertainty about authorship and intent rather than affirming them.\n\nWeighing both positions, I find the proposition demonstrated. The standard requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not authentication. Multiple independent outlets—Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP—along with the SDNY court order itself, all characterized the document as Epstein's suicide note before May 8. The \"purportedly\" language reflects responsible journalism while still reporting the attribution. The note's content and context support its characterization as a suicide-related communication. Public availability and credible reporting are established by preponderance.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the full arbitration record. The proposition asks whether, by May 8, 2026, a note was publicly available and **credibly reported** to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note or equivalent communication—not whether authorship was authenticated beyond doubt.\n\nThe admitted record establishes:\n1. **Public availability before deadline:** SDNY Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealed the note, directing the clerk to docket and release material described as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n2. **Credible reporting consensus:** Reuters (May 6), NPR (May 7), BBC (May 7), and AP (defense exhibit) all reported the public release and characterized the document as Epstein's purported suicide note or goodbye note, preserving the note's text including \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\"\n3. **Intent evidence:** The reported text, context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt), and consistent media/court framing support suicide-note or final-message interpretation.\n\nThe \"purported\" and \"not verified\" caveats reflect responsible journalism and the market rule's own wording—they do not negate that credible reporting established the required characterizations by preponderance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that before May 8, 2026, a note was publicly released via SDNY court order (May 6) and credibly reported by Reuters, NPR, BBC, and AP as Epstein's purported suicide note with final-message language. The proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not conclusive authentication; the consistent characterization across independent outlets and the official court order satisfies this standard.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":18099,"output":1112,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19211,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782796144492,"responseId":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I've received the opportunity to vote. Let me analyze the case:\n\n**Proposition:** By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\n\n**Standard:** Preponderance of the evidence.\n\n**Key evidence admitted:**\n1. **PX-1 (SDNY Order):** Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealing a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" - proves official court release before deadline\n2. **PX-2 (Reuters):** May 6 report of federal judge releasing document described as suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, with note text\n3. **PX-3 (NPR):** May 7 report confirming public release, calls it \"goodbye note,\" preserves authentication caveats\n4. **PX-4 (BBC):** May 7 report corroborating public release and note characterization\n5. **DX-1 (AP):** Defense evidence confirming public release while emphasizing provenance caveats\n\n**Analysis:**\n- **Public availability:** Uncontested - the SDNY order unsealed the note on May 6, 2026, before the May 8 deadline\n- **Credibly reported:** Multiple major credible outlets (Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP) reported on the released note before May 8\n- **Written by Epstein:** All reports describe it as \"purportedly\" written by Epstein; none authenticate