n Correctional Center, where they overlapped for about two weeks in July 2019.\n- NPR page image alt text identifies \"A copy of a suicide note purportedly written by Jeffrey Epstein in 2019,\" and a caption states a judge unsealed a note purportedly written by Epstein after a suspected suicide attempt in July 2019, a month before he was found dead.\n- NPR quotes or paraphrases attorney Bruce Barket as saying he believes the note genuine but did not officially authenticate it. Captured quote: \"We didn't ever authenticate it [with] any real handwriting analysis or something like that,\" while saying surrounding circumstances, Tartaglione's account, and similar writing led them to be comfortable with Epstein authorship.\n- NPR reports DOJ told NPR by email that the note had not yet been authenticated and that this was the first time DOJ was seeing it. It also reports DOJ lawyers did not object to release and disclaimed knowledge of the accuracy of Tartaglione's factual narrative.\n- NPR reports Judge Karas gave parties one week to propose redactions to other filings and that Barket said those documents could answer more questions about the note.\n\nLimits/caveats: NPR did not authenticate the note and reports DOJ had not authenticated it; the probative value is credible public reporting of public release and the character of the reported note, with explicit adverse authentication limits.\n\n[defendant] PX-1 SDNY access order\nUNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT, SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK, United States of America v. Nicholas Tartaglione, Case No. 16-CR-832 (KMK), ORDER, Kenneth M. Karas, United States District Judge, dated May 6, 2026.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- The Court received a request from the New York Times to unseal certain materials filed in the case.\n- The Times sought access to: \"A suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Mr. Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Mr. Tartaglione's attorneys in this case (the 'Note').\"\n- The Court determined that the Times' request to unseal the alleged \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by . . . Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by . . . Tartaglione's attorneys in this case\" should be granted.\n- The order recounts that Tartaglione was briefly cellmates with Jeffrey Epstein at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan while awaiting trial.\n- The order notes that the Times pointed to a Department of Justice document referencing the Note, and that according to that document, the Note predated Epstein's death by over a week and predated Epstein being placed in a different cell from Tartaglione.\n- The Court concluded that the Note was a judicial document and that public access to the Note promotes accountability and public confidence in the administration of justice.\n- The Court wrote that no party identified any competing consideration that would justify sealing the Note, and agreed that Defendant's repeated public discussion of the Note's contents constituted waiver of attorney-client privilege as to the document.\n- Conclusion: \"For the reasons set forth above, the Times' request is granted as to the Note. The Clerk of Court is respectfully directed to docket a copy of the material that was placed in the vault on May 20, 2021, and to unseal the original material placed in the vault on May 20, 2021. The Court reserves decision as to the remainder of the materials requested by the Times.\"\n- SO ORDERED. Dated: May 6, 2026, White Plains, New York. Kenneth M. Karas, United States District Judge.\n\nLimits/caveats captured: the official order granted access and used the 'purportedly authored' framing; it did not itself authenticate Epstein's handwriting, resolve chain of custody, or decide the subjective intent of the note.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Official SDNY order text capture: Tartaglione unsealing order (ev_3ed1398d0c91_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-3ed1398d0c91)\nSource: https://www.nysd.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/2026-05/16cr832%20-%20Tartaglione%20Order%20-%2026.5.6.pdf\nSHA-256: `3ed1398d0c9152000129fa3400c1a3299338e0c732e20a3f09df0f2ad2d70268`\nBytes: 2353\nRelevance: Official source establishing that Judge Kenneth M. Karas granted the New York Times request to unseal the note before the May 8 deadline and described it as an alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Reuters/KFGO report capture: New York judge releases purported Epstein suicide note (ev_6b611c640731_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-6b611c640731)\nSource: https://kfgo.com/2026/05/06/new-york-judge-releases-purported-epstein-suicide-note/\nSHA-256: `6b611c640731a8ce06c33ab57fa1e536cddd52faaff43a426ca82e9abee28ece`\nBytes: 2426\nRelevance: Credible wire-service report before May 8 that a federal judge released a document described as a suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, with the note text and authenticity/custody caveats.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] NPR report capture: purported Epstein suicide note unsealed (ev_d9d8f4d4776e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-d9d8f4d4776e)\nSource: https://www.npr.org/2026/05/07/nx-s1-5814808/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note\nSHA-256: `d9d8f4d4776ea5454dfb52225cd3a2dd7f0addd1ddc359b25852a5fd5c774757`\nBytes: 2546\nRelevance: Independent public-media report before the May 8 deadline confirming the note was publicly released and preserving authentication/adverse caveats.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] BBC report capture: US judge releases Jeffrey Epstein's purported suicide note (ev_eb7c336c85a2_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-eb7c336c85a2)\nSource: https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd7pd0rqwreo\nSHA-256: `eb7c336c85a2e6f2353bb1062b273e37c88345f2bbb6f4197a9ad87172adc948`\nBytes: 2369\nRelevance: Independent international report before the May 8 deadline corroborating public release, note text, claimed source, and non-verification caveats.\n\n[defendant arguments] AP report capture: DOJ first seeing Epstein note and source-chain caveats (ev_4f315084b1b6_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4f315084b1b6)\nSource: https://apnews.com/article/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-note-5297f49736e625a06d0db3c7b737b997\nSHA-256: `4f315084b1b67752e7a1bdd9335d4fdb3be9134131938026864f31913da5459b`\nBytes: 2922\nRelevance: Defense evidence showing the note surfaced through Tartaglione's unrelated case rather than DOJ Epstein records, DOJ said it had not authenticated and was seeing it for the first time, Tartaglione had self-protective reasons for preserving it, and Epstein reportedly accused Tartaglione before recanting.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Plaintiff Source-Chain And Adverse-Check Ledger\nRecord scan found only packet files and openings before plaintiff evidence submissions. Native searches targeted the SDNY order, Reuters, NPR, and BBC. The official SDNY PDF was downloaded from nysd.uscourts.gov on 2026-06-30, size 128,992 bytes, SHA-256 7225441cb802084e2b9485ebc2c6d246fbfa08e109fe650cb14f445dc4745ca0; binary upload was abandoned after base64 shell output truncation risk, so a focused text capture was submitted. Reuters/KFGO, NPR, and BBC pages were downloaded locally and hashed; focused captures were submitted. Adverse checks preserved in the evidence: no court authentication, no chain-of-custody assessment, NPR/BBC non-verification, DOJ not-yet-authenticated/not-seen caveats, and no real handwriting analysis. Remaining gap: no standalone official docketed note image was captured.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-chain and gap ledger\nReviewed all plaintiff argument exhibits and submitted AP source-chain capture as DX-1. The record establishes public release and reporting before May 8, but still lacks the full court note image, handwriting authentication, chain-of-custody proof, the underlying DOJ document referenced by the order, full NYT petition/source materials, or a court/official finding that Epstein wrote the note or intended it as a suicide note/final message. The decisive limitation is that each credible source preserves non-authentication and provenance caveats.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T05:23:54.836104186Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C3","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C3","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":890351,"role_id":"council","turn_number":11},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":16,"version":22}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782796144488},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I've received the opportunity to vote. Let me analyze the case:\n\n**Proposition:** By May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available.\n\n**Standard:** Preponderance of the evidence.\n\n**Key evidence admitted:**\n1. **PX-1 (SDNY Order):** Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealing a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\" - proves official court release before deadline\n2. **PX-2 (Reuters):** May 6 report of federal judge releasing document described as suicide note purportedly written by Epstein, with note text\n3. **PX-3 (NPR):** May 7 report confirming public release, calls it \"goodbye note,\" preserves authentication caveats\n4. **PX-4 (BBC):** May 7 report corroborating public release and note characterization\n5. **DX-1 (AP):** Defense evidence confirming public release while emphasizing provenance caveats\n\n**Analysis:**\n- **Public availability:** Uncontested - the SDNY order unsealed the note on May 6, 2026, before the May 8 deadline\n- **Credibly reported:** Multiple major credible outlets (Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP) reported on the released note before May 8\n- **Written by Epstein:** All reports describe it as \"purportedly\" written by Epstein; none authenticate handwriting; DOJ hadn't authenticated it\n- **Intent as suicide note:** The note text (\"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\") and context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt) support this characterization\n\nThe key question is whether \"credibly reported to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note\" is satisfied by multiple credible outlets reporting it as a \"purported suicide note\" with explicit caveats about authentication.\n \nThe proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not definitive authentication. Multiple independent outlets reported the note was Epstein's purported suicide note before the deadline, based on an official court unsealing. The \"purported\" language reflects responsible journalism rather than undermining the reporting's credibility—the proposition's standard is met when credible sources report these claims, even while noting authentication limitations. The court order itself characterizes the document as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein,\" and major outlets reported this characterization before the deadline. This appears to satisfy the \"credibly reported\" standard.\n\nYet the defendant raises a valid concern: reporting can credibly describe a claim without establishing its probable truth. The sources explicitly preserved uncertainty about authorship and intent rather than affirming them.\n\nWeighing both positions, I find the proposition demonstrated. The standard requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not authentication. Multiple independent outlets—Reuters, NPR, BBC, AP—along with the SDNY court order itself, all characterized the document as Epstein's suicide note before May 8. The \"purportedly\" language reflects responsible journalism while still reporting the attribution. The note's content and context support its characterization as a suicide-related communication. Public availability and credible reporting are established by preponderance.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the full arbitration record. The proposition asks whether, by May 8, 2026, a note was publicly available and **credibly reported** to have been written by Epstein and intended as a suicide note or equivalent communication—not whether authorship was authenticated beyond doubt.\n\nThe admitted record establishes:\n1. **Public availability before deadline:** SDNY Judge Karas's May 6, 2026 order unsealed the note, directing the clerk to docket and release material described as a \"suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein.\"\n2. **Credible reporting consensus:** Reuters (May 6), NPR (May 7), BBC (May 7), and AP (defense exhibit) all reported the public release and characterized the document as Epstein's purported suicide note or goodbye note, preserving the note's text including \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye.\"\n3. **Intent evidence:** The reported text, context (found after July 2019 suicide attempt), and consistent media/court framing support suicide-note or final-message interpretation.\n\nThe \"purported\" and \"not verified\" caveats reflect responsible journalism and the market rule's own wording—they do not negate that credible reporting established the required characterizations by preponderance.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves by preponderance that before May 8, 2026, a note was publicly released via SDNY court order (May 6) and credibly reported by Reuters, NPR, BBC, and AP as Epstein's purported suicide note with final-message language. The proposition requires credible reporting of authorship and intent, not conclusive authentication; the consistent characterization across independent outlets and the official court order satisfies this standard.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":18099,"output":1112,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19211,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782796144492,"responseId":"gen-1782796144-SHS8KSvayf0bDJPoYoya","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_46f2f8abc9794e3e97e5745a","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C3\ncase_id: arb-ex08-20260630044803\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nremaining_ms: 865029\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex08-20260630044803\",\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:23:54.836104186Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":865029,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":11}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C3\ncase_id: arb-ex08-20260630044803\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C3\nremaining_ms: 865029\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex08-20260630044803\",\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T05:23:54.836104186Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C3\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":865029,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":11}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex08-20260630044803","member_id":"C3","ok":true,"result":{"text":"Council vote accepted."},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":true,"deadline":"2026-06-30T05:23:54.836104186Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C3","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C3","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":865029,"role_id":"council","turn_number":11}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"submit_council_vote"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782796169808},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The vote was accepted. The case shows \"completed\": true for my turn. The tool returned \"Council vote accepted.\" I should report this and stop.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"My vote was accepted. The council has recorded my vote that the proposition is **demonstrated** by a preponderance of the evidence."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":18746,"output":66,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18812,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782796169808,"responseId":"gen-1782796170-6J23sTDiaUyEjfai7QHY","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}],"willRetry":false}
